J5kXGNA4h9iqplALKP7Y3A.text: My boyfriend and I had passed this place multiple times because it's right next to Food City and we go  there often. On Sunday morning we were looking for a new breakfast spot and we were surprised that this place came up on yelp because when I think of sweet desert cafe I think... desert. Or bakery or some sort so after reading the reviews there were more good ones than bad so we thought to give it a try. Originally I was craving something sweet like pancakes or crepes but when I got there I decided to go with a breakfast burrito and my boyfriend ordered a steak and egg omelette. When you go in you don't sit down to order you go up to the counter, order and then they bring it out to you. The place is small enough to where they can just bring it out without knowing a table number. It's a very cute place with a good vibe and my personal experience wasn't necessarily BAD, but it could have been better. When my boyfriend ordered his omelette, the lady repeated "okay, steak and egg omelette?" And he said yes. We ordered 2 coffees and sat down. The coffee took a little over 5 minutes to come out to us which is fine but no water cups were provided while we waited. We had to ask for those later. When we got our food two burritos were brought out and just sat in front of us. He ordered an omelette, not a burrito. I didn't know which was mine so we asked and she didn't know either which was shocking... shouldn't you know the difference between the two? Anyway, he was fine with the steak and egg burrito instead of the omelette. He said his was okay and mine was just really salty. It was hard to fully enjoy the flavors because of the amount of salt. The standard breakfast burrito has eggs, bacon, ham and cheese. Maybe if there were potatoes or something in it the salty ness would have been less overwhelming. A couple sat down next to us and the lady had ordered a BLT and when the BLT came out, she took a bite and noticed that the bacon was missing... from a bacon lettuce and tomato sandwich. So it was just lettuce and tomato. She goes up and tells the lady at the counter and the lady apologized and brought out a side of bacon for her. The customer ordered an egg with her BLT as well which she did receive with the sandwich, but when her bacon was brought out the excuse was "they were just really focused on your egg." That was a little frustrating to hear. Don't make excuses just apologize and give her what she asked for. Even when my boyfriend received his wrong order she said "I heard you say burrito not omelette" but she repeated the order back to us and confirmed she heard omelette in the beginning. Nothing irritates me more than excuses. I'm sorry but just take responsibility that you made a mistake or that your cooks made a mistake and don't try to turn it around on your customers. The lady wasn't rude, but she was just making excuses. The place is small and pretty packed when busy so I can see how only having one or two people operating the front house can be difficult but maybe have more people working during your peak hours because I think that was the reason for the mistakes... too busy and not enough staff. I think the place has potential to be better but I can't say this is a place that I will wake up and say "I want to go here for breakfast" because it just wasn't anything special. Oh and I almost forgot, I took my coffee with me when I left because it was served in a styrofoam cup with a lid. By the time I got home 10 minutes later I picked up the cup out of the cup holder and it actually broke in half. Yep. The cup broke in half and the coffee spilled all over my cup holders. So the coffee was still too hot and basically melted the cup. Can't say I expected that. I don't like making negative reviews but my reason is just to let the owners know you have potential to be better but just be a little more attentive and maybe invest in some better coffee cups, stop making excuses for your mistakes and maybe offer customers water upon arrival so when it takes too long to make coffee at least we have something to sip on. It's Arizona and it's hot out, water is essential.

Being our first time, we were going to order 4 sandwiches to try, but the owner suggested we get two kids croissants for our daughter (aged 3) and son (17 months) to save money and it would be the perfect size for their small appetites. I ordered the Pizza Panini and the Beef Pastrami to split with my husband. The service was a little sluggish, but the staff are so friendly and the food itself was worth the wait! Tried the pizza panini first and the focaccia texture was astounding! Crisp, flakey exterior and an airy, fluffy interior, it was perfectly toasted and paired well with the rich tomato sauce, mozzarella and pepperoni. This one was hands down our favorite between the two. The beef pastrami was good and had a very green, herb-y flavor and with your choice of cheese and veggies, was definitely a hearty sandwich. We ordered their ice blended mocha and salted caramel coffees, and they were just perfect. Sweet, creamy and almost a dessert in themselves! Their flavor was on point!  We ended our meal with a chewy, fudgy brownie topped with vanilla ice cream and, like piranha, we devoted it in seconds! My few notes for improvement would be that the high top pub tables were not the easiest to seat two small kids. One of us had to eat with the little guy on our lap since they didn't offer high chair seating, which makes sense since the tables were too tall for a high chair to meet up to anyhow.  The other critical note is that they do not offer sides with their sandwiches, so if you are super hungry, plan accordingly. Other than that, this is my new fave eatery in Tempe!

CWuW4PqDxuS-l5wg351-BA.text: My breath smells like cat food!  ...if cat food was actually tuna pate.  Wow! What a GREAT lunch! This place is a True mom-and-pop shop! The owners are seriously the sweetest people ever. Passionate about their menu, they'll tell you how everything is made, ask about what you like, what they suggest, et cetera. They will talk and talk, show you videos of creme brulee being cracked open on their Instagram, and call you over to watch them dress their desserts. They'll drag you into a long and pleasant conversation about how a retired professor from Venezuela found her True passion for baking! The husband and wife will tell you how they're making the desert (not a typo for dessert) more sweet --- Sweet Desert is where it's at!  I had ordered myself a Tuna Pate Panini after the husband, a charismatic Spanish gentleman, convinced me I had to try it.  For the record, Tuna Pate is tuna salad.  I ended up trading my pal Linh L. for half his Ham & Salami Panini so I can try two flavors but I'll be honest, I wish I kept my panini for myself because it was amazing! I know you're wondering how someone can be this excited over tuna salad but I was.  The homemade pesto paired with the tuna nicely and I had ordered it with European Swiss Cheese. It was refreshing, light to the taste, and incredibly creamy. I couldn't get enough.  The Ham & Salami was alright but that Tuna Pate Panini was money!  For dessert, Linh and I shared a freshly baked Tres Leches (we got a front row seat as the owner drizzled hot caramel over it!) and a Creme Brulee as per Ann R. and Amber R.'s suggestion. My homies know what's up because that might have been the best creme brulee I ever had. It had a very light and subtle vanilla taste, it was ridiculously smooth, and it wasn't too sweet! And that crust... the best!  The Tres Leches was also enjoyable.  It has a meringue topping and not whipped cream.  The caramel had hardened on top by the time we ordered a slice and gave it a nice crunchy texture.  Between the tres leches and creme brulee though, the creme brulee stole my heart.    Anyways, I'm completely head-over-heels over this place and y'all need to stop in and fall in love too!

Everything appeared to be cooked to order and came out steaming hot. I definitely burned my mouth on that burrito because it was so good that I couldn't wait for it to cool down.  The croissant breakfast sandwich was solid, the ingredients were fairly simple but put together well on a massive croissant. The porky burrito (can also be an omelette) was stuffed with really soft scrambled eggs, sausage, bacon, ham. The tortilla was soft and chewy and the burrito was topped with just a little bit of extra meat and cheese. If this was on my way to work, I'd be ordering this at least once a week, if not more. By far the best breakfast burrito I've had in years. If they renamed to porky burrito cafe, honestly they'd still get 5 stars from me.  All that being said, their sweet stuff appears to be good too. Our mixed berry crepes were topped with a ton of berries and filled with a slightly sweet cream that made them feel really light. Prices were super reasonable, the inside was small but clean, and the staff was super friendly.
